This database schema leverages PostgreSQL to support dynamic DAGs, parallel tasks, and crash recovery
.
1️⃣ workflows & workflow_runs
workflows: Stores reusable workflow templates. Columns: id (UUID), name, version, created_at, updated_at
.
workflow_runs: Stores execution instances. Columns: id, workflow_id (FK), status (PENDING, RUNNING, SUCCESS, FAILED), triggered_by, started_at, completed_at
.
2️⃣ task_definitions & task_dependencies
task_definitions: Defines DAG nodes. Columns: id, workflow_id, name, task_type (CLONE, BUILD, TEST, REPORT), timeout_seconds, max_retries
.
task_dependencies: Defines DAG edges. Columns: id, workflow_id, parent_task_id, child_task_id
.
3️⃣ task_runs (Critical Execution State)
Tracks exact execution states to power self-healing. Columns: id, workflow_run_id, task_definition_id, status (PENDING, READY, RUNNING, SUCCESS, FAILED), retry_count, worker_id, started_at, last_heartbeat, error_message
.
State Machine: PENDING → READY → RUNNING → SUCCESS / FAILED. If FAILED and under max retries → READY. If retry exhausted → DLQ
.
4️⃣ task_logs & workers
task_logs: Stores execution logs (stdout, stderr)
.
workers: Tracks active worker pods (heartbeats)
.
Crucial Indexes: To prevent slow scheduling, indexes are required on status, workflow_run_id, parent_task_id, and worker_id
.
